I enjoyed reading this book in a different way than others. It was transformative & thoughtful, as well as entertaining. I was captivated throughout, and wholly satisfied when it came to its satisfying close.

The first 2/3 of the story teetered more in the realm of speculative fiction with hints of scifi. The world presented is a tangible and believable future that feels within reach. Of course, both genres are simply two sides of the same coin, and are crafted expertly to become one.

The story didnt transport me into an escapist experience, but rather uncovered a deeply reflective part of myself to contemplate. Nagamatsu taps into the blind hope invoked in a desperate situation, in a society that is forced to move on after individual tragedy.

So, make sure to get out there and start learning! And when you're ready to take your climate change knowledge to the next level, be sure to follow Climate Club on social media and sign up for our newsletter on our website. Click below for the full article.

Conclusion - There are plenty of ways to stay informed about the latest developments in climate change. Whether you prefer to delve into dense books and studies, or you're more of a social media and YouTube aficionado, there's an option out there for everyone.

8 Write down everything you learn - With daily bombardment of information, it can be easy to forget all the concepts that we learn. A habit that helps me massively is to write every insight I gain on a notepad. This will drastically improve understanding of climate change.

Lectures and workshops can also be found, where you can learn and ask any burning questions you have about the greenhouse effect, deforestation or anything else. Most of these are hosted by experts, meaning you can meet them and directly learn from them.

A few platforms where you can look out for upcoming events are Facebook, LinkedIn or Eventbrite. There are countless environmental networking events in the UK, and one that I never miss out on is People, Planet, Pint in London.

7. Networking events ‚Äì Contrary to what you may think, these aren‚Äôt just for those fancy finance guys in tailored suits talking about the stock market. There are more relaxed events for those of us looking to have conversations about Climate change, over a coffee or a beer.

It can be used as a tool to have conversations about topics we want to learn more about, one of which is our impact on the natural world. A few ways I do this is by following relevant hashtags, trending topics, content creators, and people with similar interests.

6. Social Media - We can be a bit apprehensive about entering the crazy land of social media, where a million messages and comments fly across the internet every second. But there is a lot of value to be found in engaging with others online to discuss the environment.

5. Documentaries ‚Äì These give you visual aspect of climate change, rather than a bunch of stats and graphs. A good reminder of global warming is seeing a time-lapse of an iceberg melting over a few decades or the effects of flooding in poorer countries.

4. YouTube - We all rely on YouTube for those 'How to' videos and to learn about pretty much anything. Why not use it to learn about the environment? There‚Äôs a ton of content creators who put out great videos. My favourites are 'Simon Clark' and 'Our Changing Climate'.

The latest findings on the environment are found in these journals, written by industry leading experts. Whether you're interested in atmospheric science or carbon taxes; there's something for everyone. Some examples are 'Nature' and 'Environmental Research Letters'.

3. Studies - I don't blame you if you skip past this bit but hear me out first. Reading peer reviewed journals can be tedious when they are filled thousands of complicated stats and graphs. However, this is the closest you can get to reliable information about climate change.

This is useful when learning about a complicated and multi-faceted subject like Climate change. A few good ones I read in 2022 were 'Uninhabitable Earth' by David Wallace Wells and 'Our Biggest Experiment' by Alice Bell.

2. Read books - There's nothing like getting lost in a 600-page mammoth of a book on the intricacies of the global carbon cycle to really get the blood pumping. Books are great because they can give you an in depth understanding for any particular topic.

It‚Äôs important to have critical thinking when reading blogs because it can get hectic trying to wrap your head around different sides of an argument. A few good blogs are the Guardian, TreeHugger and Ethical hour. But the best place to start is right here at Climate Club!

Furthermore, articles give you an understanding of breaking news and up-to-date information. By reading articles and blogs, you can stay informed about the latest findings and how they might impact our understanding of the issue.

1. Read Articles/Blogs - This is a good way to learn about climate change because it allows you to access a wide range of perspectives on the topic. By reading from different sources, you can get a well-rounded understanding and gain insights from a variety of writers.

Learning about the environment is hard because there are a lot of complicated terms we hear constantly, but no one ever tells us what they actually mean. Like greenhouse gases, atmospheric concentrations, and tipping points. And don't get me started on the political angle.
